  <body>
    <div xml:id="PN202">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>veṭcik kāṉattu vēṭṭuva rāṭṭak</l>
<l>kaṭci kāṇāk kaṭamā nallēṟu</l>
<l>kaṭaṟumaṇi kiḷarac citaṟupoṉ miḷirak</l>
<l>kaṭiya kataḻu neṭuvaraip paṭappai</l>
<l>veṉṟi nilaiiya viḻupuka ḻoṉṟi</l>
<l>yirupāṟ peyariya vurukeḻu mūtūrk</l>
<l>kōṭipala vaṭukkiya poruṇumak kutaviya</l>
<l>nīṭunilai yaraiyattuk kēṭuṅ kēḷiṉi</l>
<l>nuntai tāya niṟaivuṟa veytiya</l>
<l>voliyaṟ kaṇṇip pulikaṭi māa</l>
<l>ṉumpō laṟivi ṉumaru ḷoruvaṉ</l>
<l>pukaḻnta ceyyuṭ kaḻāat talaiyai</l>
<l>yikaḻntataṉ payaṉē yiyaṟē raṇṇa</l>
<l>levvi tolkuṭip paṭīiyar maṟṟivar</l>
<l>kaivaṇ pāri makaḷi reṉṟaveṉ</l>
<l>ṟēṟṟāp puṉco ṉōṟṟiciṟ peruma</l>
<l>viṭuttaṉeṉ velīiyarniṉ vēlē yaṭukkat</l>
<l>tarumpaṟa malarnta karuṅkāl vēṅkai</l>
<l>māttakaṭ ṭoḷvī tāya tuṟuka</l>
<l>lirumpuli varippuṟaṅ kaṭukkum</l>
<l>peruṅkal vaippi ṉāṭukiḻa vōyē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>With gardens on the tall mountain, where races fast (4)</l>
<l>the good bull of the wild cow that does not see a refuge (2)</l>
<l>when hunter chase [it] in the Veṭci forest, (1)</l>
<l>so that sapphires shine up in the wilderness, while scattered gold rolls about, (3)</l>
<l>the beautiful/fearful ancient town that was named for two parts, (6)</l>
<l>being one in excellent praise when victory was permanent, (5)</l>
<l>about the loss of long-standing Araiyam now hear (8)</l>
<l>that helped you with the wealth they had piled in many crore: (7)</l>
<l>o Pulikaṭimāal with a flourishing chaplet (10)</l>
<l>who fully attained the heritage of your father, (9)</l>
<l>[it was] the result of disregarding (13ab)</l>
<l>Kaḻāattalai with [his] verses in praise (12)</l>
<l>of one among you with knowledge like your’s, (11)</l>
<l>  o majesty with an advancing chariot. (13cd)</l>
<l>Bear with my unclear lowly words, o great man, (16)</l>
<l>that said “the daughters of Pāri generous of hand, </l>
<l>may they settle in the ancient clan of Evvi.” (14f.)</l>
<l>I leave [them here]/I take leave [of you]. May you spear be victorious, (17a-c)</l>
<l>o lord of a land in the region of big rocks, (21)</l>
<l>where the thick stones spread over with the bright blossoms with dark outer petals (19)</l>
<l>of the black-trunked kino tree that bloomed so that [its] bud ceased on the mountain side (17d-18)</l>
<l>resemble that striped backs of large tigers. (20)  </l>
</lg>
    </div>
